segments.text: Acting dean for a year and then Mews is hired as the dean and you are the associate dean.
Associate dean for graduate programs and research.
Alright, by then how big was the business program?
It's growing.
Yeah, it's huge by then.
It's now getting ready to get the blocker, well the next, the year following it gets, well as a matter of fact they moved in right after I
replaced you.
So I stayed until I guess May as associate dean or April, but I remember once they decided I was to do it.
You left early as I recall, didn't you?
July 1.
I thought you left earlier than that.
I mean 1980, excuse me.
Well, in any event, I guess I was supposed to serve until the end of August, and I left.
Originally, it was going to be August, and I said, no, let me get out there and get my feet on the ground.
Which is a good thing to do.
If I had to do it over again, I'd do it the same way.
Mews had been a department head.
And dean of a little college in West Virginia.
And then came here.
You chaired the committee.
Yes, yes.
I was on it.
Describe him as dean.
He did a good job.
He sat down with every member of the faculty, came in early as I recall, and did that.
did start planning for further growth and particularly quality growth.
I think he instituted a number of procedures that got other people's attention because not too long after he was made a deputy chancellor.
Were there any key decisions you recall that really helped to

determine the growth and progress of business under in those years i think the i don't remember key decisions i remember uh that we had some pretty good department heads and the money was flowing and um enrollment was skyrocketing and enrollment was
women were flocking into particularly accounting.
Even then, close to half of the enrollees in the accounting program were females.
So, of course, there's no question but what the role of females on this campus made a major difference.
Can you give any examples that you recall
of the real world out there showing their acceptance of the progress of A&M?
Do you remember any businesses changing their policy about hiring A&M people or anything?
Well, first of all,

in past years not necessarily from the business program but from the college petroleum engineering people and so forth had succeeded to pretty important positions presidencies in many cases and uh... people like bill adams and before him bill eckles
worked hard at developing the Aggie ties with these people for the executive development program.
So I think the executive development program played a non-trivial role
and getting business people on campus.
And you know this as well as I do, when they hit the campus they just awed by the quality, the character of the students, the friendliness of the place.
And of course this was during the Vietnam War times and there weren't major uprisings on our campus.
We were
the model from a conservative businessman's point of view.
We were the model of decorum.
The story was that the only time the students marched on the president's house, on Jack Williams' house, was for some.
I think to welcome him.
To welcome him, yeah, that was right.
Describe Bill Mews as dean, his manner, his style.
He was a leader.
It was pretty clear that he was a leader, but he was a democratic leader.
He got input and basically, I felt really part of the program for the 10 months or 11 months that I was his associate dean.
He was innovative.
He came out of marketing.
And so he knew what he needed to do in terms of, I think he really did do a pretty good job of marketing the program nationally.
I'm sure he was effective when he went to meetings such as the AACSB's meetings, national meetings.
He was an effective recruiter.
Did we have, did you all have
a business program somewhere else that you kind of used as a model?
Was there any school or schools trying to follow that pattern?
No, I can't remember that we really did.
It would be worth asking Bill about if he did.
I was only in for
a year, what I did try to do was get some order out of what I thought was kind of not the best way, from my point of view, handling determining salaries and things like that for department heads.
I had the whole department head group sit down and review all of our salaries.
So you were associate dean for a year and then back to the department, or did you stay back to the department?
Well, no, sorry.
I was selected to be dean of faculties from there.
Forgot about it.
Review for me the process, that selection process.
Well, I debated hemmed and hawed about whether I would even put my name in the pot.
Chuck called me and asked me to do it.
McCandless.
McCandless, yeah, and I did.
And I ended up being one of the finalists.
There were three, I guess.
Stewart in English, I think.
What's his name in physics, whose wife Carolyn Adair.
Tom Adair.
I think he might have been.
For whatever reason, I got selected.
And how did you learn you'd been selected?
Did you get a letter or a phone call?
I was asked to come over and see Mac Prescott.
Okay.
And so you took over in summer of 80, and this was- Within a month or two, Jarvis Miller was gone.
Right.
How did you hear that news?
Ah, you've probably heard the story.
Hubert had started these
programs, it's not quite the right word, events where the board, after its board meeting, would go somewhere and meet the faculty and staff of colleges.
We and architecture were at the Ramada Inn, and what's his name from?
Tyler came marching in and said, why don't we fire your president?
This was said to the first people who happened to see him as he came in.
And you talk about a grass fire on a prairie, I mean it just swept through the place like
Nobody, I don't think anybody, well, I didn't, certainly had no clue that this was going on.

I didn't either, and I had left the day before to drive to, that was a Wednesday, and my wife and I had had lunch with Ken and Ann Pierce, veterinary medicine, old Presbyterian friends, and we left Tuesday after lunch, spent the night in Fort Stockton, got to El Paso Wednesday night,
went to the president's house to look more carefully at what it was going to be like.
And we got to our motel at 1030 Mountain Time, and there was a note there saying, urgent call Dr. Prescott at President Miller's house.
And I asked the clerk, and she said the phone call had come at 730 Mountain Time.
So it was then three hours later.
My wife said, are you going to call?
And I said, no, it's too late.
It's 1130 there.
Whatever's done is done.
what do you think happened?
Well, I have no idea.
But I said, this is not Mac Prescott calling to say good luck.
We're wishing you well.
I said, this is serious.
Yeah, it's like a death or something.
And I said, perhaps one of the Miller daughters had an accident.
Who knows?
But then, in attempted humor, I said, the board's there.
Anything's possible.
By 8 o'clock,

By 7 o'clock Mountain Time, 8 o'clock Central Time, I'd had calls from three different newspaper reporters who found me out there asking for my comment on what had happened, and I didn't, until they told me, I didn't know what had happened.
What was the general reaction of?
Well, a shock.
Most, I don't know how Dean's,
generally reacted to how Jarvis Miller functioned as a president.
I was not impressed myself, particularly he had a lieutenant who was a political hack.
I can't remember his name.
Steve Pringle.
Pringle.
I mean you thought you were talking to a... How did, do you remember any of Mack's first
Well, Mack, I think, was appalled.
I think he was.
Yeah.
Because they were pretty close.
Yes.
And, all right, then Chuck Sampson's appointment as interim was announced almost immediately?
Yeah.
In fact, I think maybe that night.
I'm not sure.
But soon thereafter.
All right.
When did  how soon
did Jarvis vacate the office and Chuck occupied?
Boy, I think it was very quickly.
As I recall, Jarvis Miller, well, after the event, when he knew he was fired, he sent notes to everybody but, what's his name?
Weisenbaker.
Weisenbaker.
And I don't know that he came back to the office much except to clean out the desk.
I really don't know.
Did Mr. Weisenbaker in small talk over there give any justification or reason or explanation?
I never talked to him over there.
I've never heard.
I just heard it all hearsay.
He just said he was fired.
I understand through very indirect word of mouth that when they...
confronted Jarvis with what they had done, that one of them supposedly said, you refused to shake hands with an A&M graduate.

Well, I was seated about three feet from where that happened on the stage at the spring commencement, and when we got into the letterman's lounge where we put on our caps and gowns and so forth, I overheard a number of the board members saying, damn right, serves her right, I wouldn't have shaken hands with her either.
I didn't remember anybody that day saying that that was bad.
I'm trying to remember.
I was there too.
Yes, you were.
Because I remember.
We were both on stage.
I remember Jarvis.
walking toward Mack's back and doing this, or something like that, and Mack had to go up and take his place.
And I'm trying to remember if there was a gasp in the audience or not.
There were a few people kind of going, like, Chuck took over.
Did he do, did he have any
key meetings with you, key people in the first weeks?
He continued the Jarvis Miller breakfast, which were what, once a month?
I think so.
Yeah, although we backed off from the steak and eggs and everything and got down to cereal and toast and whatnot.
Were there still
once-a-week APC meetings?
Yes.
Of course, those were presided over by Mack.
Yes, yes.
All right, now describe, make believe that I didn't know Mack's style of leadership.
Describe Mack Prescott as a chief academic officer.
Well, you knew where he stood.
I don't need to say that.
I thought he presided well.
I mean, he was crisp, and we took business in order, and I was impressed.
I liked Mack.
What were his, did he have any pet peeves, foibles?
Oh, he would, he got upset over, not really upset, but he could get concerned about...
a faculty member who kind of went off the deep end on something or other.
But he, you know, he took it in his stride.
I enjoyed the
the little meetings that we had with him which now of course have grown into health conventions and there's no longer the intimacy and decision making that was really a pleasure in the early years.
Oh I can remember when you talk about being upset when he had to trot over to justify the budget
with Chuck Sampson and the picky little green eye shaded people were allowed to climb all over this, that, or the other little thing.
Mack said he almost went over the table after, who was that jerk that was, have to take that out, that person who was an assistant chancellor over there.
Ah.
I think he's finally retired.
I don't know.
Anyway, but he would ask about a secretary's salary.
Talk about picky eunuch.
Petty.
Did you notice any changes in direction or emphases?
Did anybody under Sampson?
No.
Not really.
I think he was really a caretaker.
Every night he would go out with two big briefcases full of stuff, put them in the trunk of the Cadillac, and drive home.
The next morning it would take these.
Presumably he'd signed his name all night long or something.
Now, he quickly occupied the office in the Koch building.
that Jarvis had offered.
Okay.
And now you served from 1980 to 19 what?
Ninety.
Ninety.
So you served ten years as dean of faculties.
During that period, who were the presidents?
Will Sampson, of course, was replaced by Vandiver.
And although he was off the wall, sometimes he was fun to work with.
Then who followed him?
And he was followed by... Mobley?
Mobley.
Okay.
Alright, let's talk about Vandiver.
How did you and others become aware that Vandiver was under consideration?
From Ed Cooper.
who plotted where the airplane went.
This may have been an after, something we learned afterwards, but he did know that the plane went up to Denton, the University plane with Regents on it.
And it happened pretty quickly, as I recall.
It wasn't much time wasted.
Because didn't the board say that they would have a president by September the 1st?
Yeah, and they did.
Were you and others aware of whether or not Sampson was even considered for the job permanently?
No.
There were people who were very upset that he wasn't, but
I certainly wasn't one of them.
I've not heard of whether he was or wasn't.
He was a very nice man.
Yes.
But I imagine he was sort of a Peter Principle thing.
He probably did a good job as head of civil engineering.
Well, see, and he wasn't even head of civil engineering at the time he was born.
No.
No, he wasn't.
All right.
Do you remember how you all heard that Vandiver was officially the new president?
No, I don't.
I guess it must have been a phone call to Mack.
Describe your first impression of him.
Of Vandiver?
Vandiver.
Well, I liked him.
He's a jovial guy.
Very soon, though, he did exhibit some rather strange behavior.
Such as?
Such as?
going out on a pistol range and firing a pistol.
I seem to remember that he wanted a license to carry a gun.
He had a bodyguard under consideration.
I saw somebody walk in that might have been that person.
So there were things that he did that were unusual.
He would keep people waiting for an hour.
But there were other things he did that were just a hoot.
I mean, he'd walk into my office reading something, and he'd sit there and read something to me for a half hour that he thought it was funny, and we'd chat.
He didn't care what his schedule was.
He couldn't care less about mine.
Or he'd call me in.
You know, Mobley never walked into my office in all the time, and he was just across the hall until he moved over to the tower.
Mm-hmm.
I don't know how many times Frank walked into my office or called me into his or I wandered into his.
As you worked with Vandiver, did you develop any understanding of any unwritten rules or guidelines in succeeding with him?
I learned fairly early on that
He wasn't into management principles and that sort of thing.
I remember once he jumped on poor Howard Vestal, who was coming up with a proposal to have us all learn more about control procedures or something.
I don't remember what.
I liked Howard very much, by the way, and I know Mac did.
And Vannevar did too, but I guess.
But that was one foible he had.
I admired the man tremendously for pushing ahead on things like the Senate, when, boy, there were folks in agriculture particularly that were dead set against that kind of thing.
All right, let me turn the question then.
What were his greatest strengths?
and his greatest weaknesses?
Well his greatest strengths I think were that he knew what a real university is about.
He was really on to getting us off the AAUP list and he worked hard to do that.
He wanted us to have Phi Beta Kappa and he tried that.
He encouraged the creation of the Senate, as I said, even though, as he said, there'll be days when I'll hate myself for doing this in the spite of opposition.
He was masterful at going over and testifying before a committee in Austin.
They'd ask him some question and we'd look at it and go,
How is he going to answer that?
How would he know what the answer is?
He would come out with a flawless answer, and after we checked it out, you know, it was pretty close to the truth.
He was a genius at that.
He really handled people well.
He was good at that.
But he always kept his eye on what he should be doing.
I liked him when I would go
ask him for money for proposals.
I remember I wanted to see an expansion of the academic study leaves.
There were, what, five or six in those early days, so one year as low as four, and the formula over in Austin was never going to be implemented.
So anyway, I put together a proposal, I guess about eighty-two, three, four, somewhere in
requesting a significant sum of money from the former students and routed it with his.
I had his permission to do it, of course.
It went over, and the year that it was decided was the year that Ed Davis was the ex-president of the former students.
What they decided to do was that they would come up with, I've forgotten how many thousands of dollars, if we would match the money.
And Hed Davis a couple days later ran into me and he said, I thought maybe you'd want to shoot me.
And I said, oh my God, Hed, you did the best thing I could ever imagine.
Well, anyway, so he got enough to do 15 or 18, depending upon the level of his salary.
And I was really pleased with that.
But that was something that he really went to bat for.
He went to bat for minority hiring.
Oh.
there was a period of time when we put up all the money for a minority hire.
And then when we started splitting it as a cost saving, when Mobley came in, we split the cost with the college and had to bring in very many.
That was always a tough thing to do, to recruit intellectual blacks into a community where there's a relatively small intellectual community.
Fred McClure was the first one who told me that as a student, that we didn't have enough black professionals here
for the new black faculty member or staff member to find off-campus friends in a black community?
I'm trying to think of her name.

It was assistant to Frank Black, who said if she wanted to go to a black church where she felt comfortable, she'd have to go to Houston, where she's now vice president, I guess, still, at the University of Houston.
Alright, Vandiver, we talked about his strengths, let's go to the other extreme.
Weaknesses, well some of the wacky things that he did were.
He forgot to go to Muster the first year I remember.
Oh yeah, leading the band I guess at Rice.
You know, he had a great sense of humor, and he thought people would think it was clever.
Well, maybe he never really understood old Ags too well.
Standing people up for meetings, and sometimes he'd show up, sometimes he wouldn't.
Sometimes he said things that were preposterous, like,

he tried to catch an airplane in the Houston and he just missed it and we figured how long it would take him to get there without even stopping and turning around and coming back and he couldn't have done it.
I may take this out afterwards but overall the place moved under him.
Now he and Hubert
had been acquainted for a while.
Hubert's son had been in Vandiver's classes at Rice and so forth.
After Hubert retired, did Vandiver's relation with the system change that you knew of?
No, I wouldn't know really.
I thought that he and, oh, who succeeded Hubert?
Art Hanson.
I thought he got along well with Art Hanson.
He's got some things settled like if
if one person owned only 13% of a faculty member's salary, he couldn't dictate the salary increase as one person tried to do in agriculture.
And you know who.
Anyway, they got an agreement.
Whoever had the biggest percentage.
Now, Prescott continued as the
Chief Academic Officer under Vandiver.
For a year, I guess.
Okay.
Maybe two.
Okay.
And then he retired, and who took over?
Then Gordon Eaton.
Gordon Eaton, who had been Dean of Geosciences.
And only a year or so.
Okay.
What triggered Gordon's being selected, I think?
There were two searches.
I chaired both of them.
The first one failed.
The second one, Gordon by then had been there a year and he was really impressive.

And Vandiver had decided, oh by this time we'd also, the head of the former students association had dumped a whole bunch of money on us for teaching only awards so that they would be far greater than the research awards.
And we plotted
to get those transferred to $1,000 awards and spread among all the colleges.
I like to think it was my idea, but I don't know.
I can't remember whether it was or not.
But anyway, it turned out to be a good one.
They agreed to it.
And so these awards would go on at each college.
And Vandiver went to the one at Geosciences
And Gordon had already prepared his remarks, so he wasn't saying something because Frank was there.
And Gordon was explaining what the administration was doing to the four and to the faculty, why things were happening.
Frank was immensely impressed, because typically, I mean, you get a guy like, I won't mention any names, but some would openly deride the administration
Not me, because I was always sitting there.
I went to all these meetings.
You know, they might, or they wouldn't say anything.
More than likely, they wouldn't say anything.
But he went out of his way to explain what's going on in the head shed, as he used to call it.
And I thought that was impressive.
So did Frank.
And they got along well together.
All right, so you worked with Eaton for?
For four years, I guess, three or four years.
They were the best years.
All right, describe his style.
He was laid-back, uh,
